    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="257"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d257">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Roosevelt Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName type="from">Churchill</persName> to
                        President <persName type="to">Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d257fn1">The source text is on White House stationery;
                        Churchill’s initials are typed.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, [<date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-05">January 5,
                            1942</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. President</hi>:</p>
                <p>Please will you very kindly consider giving a few rationed carrots to the Dons to
                    help stave off trouble at Gibraltar? Every day we have the use of the harbour is
                    a gain, especially in view of some other ideas we have discussed. I am told it
                    only needs a word to Wallace.<note n="2" xml:id="d257fn2">Vice President Wallace
                        was Chairman of the Board of Economic Warfare. No direct reply by Roosevelt
                        has been found, but for related documentation, see “Concern of the United
                        States Over Maintenance of Neutrality by Spain”, <ref
                            target="frus1942v03#pg_248">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1942, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, pp. 248</ref> ff., and “Negotiations
                        Between the American Chargé at Tangier and the Spanish High Commissioner
                        Regarding Economic Aid to Spanish Zone of Morocco and Tangier”, <ref
                            target="frus1942v04#pg_439">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, pp.
                            439</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. C.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>5. 1. 42</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
